# HCDE 530 Week 2 Project Rules

## Project context
- This project analyzes `demo_responses.csv` with Python and may present results in simple static HTML.
- Prioritize clarity and beginner-friendly code over advanced abstractions.

## Directory structure (keep current)
Use this structure as the baseline and update it whenever files are added, removed, moved, or renamed:

```
HCDE 530 WEEK 2 Project/
├── .cursorrules
├── .gitignore
├── README.md
├── dashboard.html
├── demo_responses.csv
└── demo_word_count.py
```

Maintenance requirement:
- If any file changes the structure, update this section in the same task.
- Keep only meaningful project files here (exclude `.git/` internals).
- Keep names exact, including spaces and capitalization.

## Python conventions
- Use Python 3 standard library first; avoid adding dependencies unless explicitly requested.
- Keep functions small and readable; add short docstrings for non-trivial functions.
- Use descriptive variable names (`responses`, `word_counts`, `participant_id`).
- Preserve UTF-8 handling for text files.

## Data handling
- Treat `demo_responses.csv` as the source of truth for participant response data.
- Do not silently change CSV schema (`participant_id`, `role`, `response`) without user approval.
- When computing metrics, include basic sanity checks and clear output labels.

## HTML dashboard conventions
- Keep dashboards standalone and easy to open locally in a browser.
- Prefer plain HTML/CSS/JS (no framework) unless requested.
- Use clear section titles and readable defaults for charts/tables.

## Editing behavior
- Make minimal, targeted edits; avoid unrelated refactors.
- Explain changes in simple terms suitable for a student audience.
- If requirements are unclear, ask one focused clarification question before major changes.
- When creating, deleting, or renaming files, also update the directory structure section above before finishing.
